WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.379
E aí eu trago de novo o Daniel Kahneman, né?

2
00:00:02.399 --> 00:00:06.519
O Daniel Kahneman ele traz pra gente também o enigma da experiência e da memória.

3
00:00:06.940 --> 00:00:11.320
A gente fala muito sobre a experiência do cliente, a experiência do CQ,

4
00:00:12.119 --> 00:00:14.480
e o Daniel Kahneman ele desconstrói isso pra gente.

5
00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:20.480
Ele mostra que existe um viés que as pessoas não se lembram da experiência,

6
00:00:21.039 --> 00:00:24.179
elas se lembram de picos de memória.

7
00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:45.100
E aí eu vou passar um vídeo do Daniel Kahneman que explica um pouquinho esse viés da experiência da memória. and they gave up after about 40 and there were many more.

8
00:00:45.100 --> 00:00:49.960
There is a huge wave of interest in happiness among researchers.

9
00:00:49.960 --> 00:00:51.520
There is a lot of happiness coaching.

10
00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:55.119
Everybody would like to make people happier.

11
00:00:55.119 --> 00:00:57.859
But in spite of all this flood of work,

12
00:00:57.859 --> 00:01:00.380
there are several cognitive traps that sort

13
00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:03.460
of make it almost impossible to think straight about happiness.

14
00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:07.739
And my talk today will be mostly about these cognitive traps.

15
00:01:07.739 --> 00:01:11.719
This applies to laypeople thinking about their own happiness, and it applies to scholars

16
00:01:11.719 --> 00:01:16.140
thinking about happiness, because it turns out we're just as messed up as anybody else

17
00:01:16.140 --> 00:01:17.879
is.

18
00:01:17.879 --> 00:01:21.040
The first of these traps is a reluctance to admit complexity.

19
00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:26.819
It turns out that the word happiness is just not a useful word anymore

20
00:01:26.819 --> 00:01:30.439
because we apply it to too many different things.

21
00:01:30.439 --> 00:01:34.239
I think there is one particular meaning to which we might restrict it,

22
00:01:34.239 --> 00:01:38.260
but by and large this is something that we'll have to give up and we'll have

23
00:01:38.260 --> 00:01:43.180
to adopt a more complicated view of what well-being is.

24
00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:46.959
The second trap is a confusion between experience and memory.

25
00:01:46.959 --> 00:01:52.060
Basically it's between being happy in your life and being happy about your life or happy

26
00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:53.060
with your life.

27
00:01:53.060 --> 00:01:58.620
And those are two very different concepts and they're both lumped in the notion of happiness.

28
00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:01.560
And the third is, it's the focusing illusion.

29
00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:05.120
And it's the unfortunate fact that we can't think about any circumstance

30
00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:10.340
that affects well-being without distorting its importance. I mean, this is a real cognitive

31
00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:14.379
trap. There's just no way of getting it right.

32
00:02:14.379 --> 00:02:21.759
Now I'd like to start with an example of somebody who had a question and answer session after

33
00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:25.080
one of my lectures reported a story and that was

34
00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:26.080
the story.

35
00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:32.120
He said he had been listening to a symphony and it was absolutely glorious music and at

36
00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:36.759
the very end of the recording there was a dreadful screeching sound.

37
00:02:36.759 --> 00:02:42.979
And then he added really quite emotionally, it ruined the whole experience.

38
00:02:42.979 --> 00:02:47.580
But it hadn't. What it had ruined were the memory of the experience.

39
00:02:47.580 --> 00:02:49.099
He had had the experience.

40
00:02:49.099 --> 00:02:51.860
He had had 20 minutes of glorious music.

41
00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:55.520
They counted for nothing because he was left with a memory.

42
00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:58.139
The memory was ruined and the memory was all

43
00:02:58.139 --> 00:03:00.400
that he had gotten to keep.

44
00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:03.819
What this is telling us really is that we might be thinking

45
00:03:03.819 --> 00:03:08.539
of ourselves and of other people in terms of two selves.

46
00:03:08.539 --> 00:03:15.500
There is an experiencing self who lives in the present and knows the present, is capable

47
00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:19.400
of reliving the past, but basically it has only the present.

48
00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:24.460
It's the experiencing self that the doctor approaches, you know, when the doctor asks,

49
00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:27.740
does it hurt now when I touch you here?

50
00:03:27.740 --> 00:03:30.319
And then there is a remembering self.

51
00:03:30.319 --> 00:03:36.080
And the remembering self is the one that keeps score and maintains the story of our life,

52
00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:44.020
and it's the one that the doctor approaches in asking the question, how have you been

53
00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:45.000
feeling lately?

54
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:46.599
Or how was your trip to Albania?

55
00:03:46.599 --> 00:03:47.819
Or something like that.

56
00:03:47.819 --> 00:03:51.180
Those are two very different entities, the experiencing

57
00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:53.919
self and the remembering self.

58
00:03:53.919 --> 00:03:57.319
And getting confused between them is part of the mess about

59
00:03:57.319 --> 00:04:00.039
the notion of happiness.

60
00:04:00.039 --> 00:04:05.479
Now, the remembering self is a storyteller.

61
00:04:05.479 --> 00:04:09.479
And that really starts with a basic response of our memory.

62
00:04:09.479 --> 00:04:10.780
It starts immediately.

63
00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:14.520
We don't only tell stories when we set out to tell stories.

64
00:04:14.520 --> 00:04:16.800
Our memory tells us stories.

65
00:04:16.800 --> 00:04:21.240
That is, what we get to keep from our experiences is a story.

66
00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:25.699
And let me begin with one example.

67
00:04:25.699 --> 00:04:27.779
This is an old study.

68
00:04:27.779 --> 00:04:30.500
Those are actual patients undergoing a painful procedure.

69
00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:31.899
I won't go into detail.

70
00:04:31.899 --> 00:04:36.680
It's no longer painful these days, but it was painful when this study was run in the

71
00:04:36.680 --> 00:04:37.680
1990s.

72
00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:41.740
They're asked to report on their pain every 60 seconds.

73
00:04:41.740 --> 00:04:43.379
And here are two patients.

74
00:04:43.379 --> 00:04:45.339
Those are their recordings.

75
00:04:45.339 --> 00:04:48.439
And you are asked who of them suffered more.

76
00:04:48.439 --> 00:04:49.759
And it's a very easy question.

77
00:04:49.759 --> 00:04:52.459
I mean, clearly patient B suffered more.

78
00:04:52.459 --> 00:04:58.639
His colonoscopy was longer and every minute of pain that patient A had, patient B had

79
00:04:58.639 --> 00:05:00.079
and more.

80
00:05:00.079 --> 00:05:02.279
But now there is another question.

81
00:05:02.279 --> 00:05:05.699
How much did these patients think they suffered?

82
00:05:05.699 --> 00:05:07.500
And here is a surprise.

83
00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:11.839
And the surprise is that patient A had a much worse memory

84
00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:15.300
of the colonoscopy than patient B. The stories

85
00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:17.660
of the colonoscopies were different.

86
00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:23.420
And because a very critical part of a story is how it ends.

87
00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:31.399
And neither of these stories is very inspiring or great, but one of them is distinctly worse

88
00:05:31.399 --> 00:05:32.980
than the other.

89
00:05:32.980 --> 00:05:38.759
And the one that is worse is the one where pain was at its peak at the very end.

90
00:05:38.759 --> 00:05:39.759
It's a bad story.

91
00:05:39.759 --> 00:05:40.980
How do we know that?

92
00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:45.480
Because we asked these people after their colonoscopy and much later too

93
00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:48.399
how bad was the whole thing in total.

94
00:05:48.399 --> 00:05:52.319
And it was much worse for A than for B in memory.

95
00:05:52.319 --> 00:05:57.160
Now this is a direct conflict between the experiencing self and the remembering self.

96
00:05:57.160 --> 00:06:02.459
From the point of view of the experiencing self, clearly B had a worse time.

97
00:06:02.459 --> 00:06:08.100
Now what you could do with patient A, and we actually ran clinical experiments and it

98
00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:13.620
has been done and it does work, you could actually extend the colonoscopy of patient

99
00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:17.540
A by just keeping the tube in without jiggling it too much.

100
00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:25.180
That will cause the patient to suffer but just a little and much less than before.

101
00:06:25.180 --> 00:06:30.079
And if you do that for a couple of minutes, you have made the experiencing self of patient

102
00:06:30.079 --> 00:06:35.839
A worse off and you have made the remembering self of patient A a lot better off because

103
00:06:35.839 --> 00:06:43.339
now you have endowed patient A with a better story about his experience.

104
00:06:43.339 --> 00:06:47.720
What defines a story, and that is true of the stories

105
00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:50.759
that memory delivers for us, and it's also true

106
00:06:50.759 --> 00:06:52.779
of the stories that we make up.

107
00:06:52.779 --> 00:06:55.899
What defines a story are changes,

108
00:06:55.899 --> 00:06:58.740
significant moments, and endings.

109
00:06:58.740 --> 00:07:01.899
Endings are very, very important, and in this case,

110
00:07:01.899 --> 00:07:10.120
you know, the ending dominated. Now, the experiencing self lives its life continuously.

111
00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:13.339
It has moments of experience, one after the other.

112
00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:16.339
And you can ask what happens to these moments?

113
00:07:16.339 --> 00:07:18.500
And the answer is really straightforward.

114
00:07:18.500 --> 00:07:19.800
They are lost forever.

115
00:07:19.800 --> 00:07:22.879
I mean, most of the moments of our life, and I calculated,

116
00:07:22.879 --> 00:07:26.680
you know, the psychological present is said to be about three seconds long.

117
00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:30.959
That means that, you know, in a life there are about 600 million of them.

118
00:07:30.959 --> 00:07:34.500
In a month there are about 600,000.

119
00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:37.259
Most of them don't leave a trace.

120
00:07:37.259 --> 00:07:41.180
Most of them are completely ignored by the remembering self.

121
00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:45.899
And yet, somehow you get the sense that they should count. That what happens

122
00:07:45.899 --> 00:07:51.560
during these moments of experience is our life. It's the finite resource that we're

123
00:07:51.560 --> 00:07:57.980
spending while we're on this earth. And how to spend it would seem to be relevant, but

124
00:07:57.980 --> 00:08:03.899
that is not the story that our remembering self keeps for us. So we have the remembering

125
00:08:03.899 --> 00:08:07.800
self and the experiencing self, and they're really quite distinct.

126
00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:12.819
The biggest difference between them is in the handling of time.

127
00:08:12.819 --> 00:08:18.079
From the point of view of the experiencing self, if you have a vacation and the second

128
00:08:18.079 --> 00:08:24.379
week is just as good as the first, then the two-week vacation is twice as good as the

129
00:08:24.379 --> 00:08:25.399
one- week vacation.

130
00:08:25.399 --> 00:08:28.600
That's not the way it works at all for the remembering self.

131
00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:32.000
For the remembering self, the two week vacation is barely better

132
00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.500
than the one week vacation because there are no new memories added.

133
00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:38.000
You have not changed the story.

134
00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.000
And in this way, time is actually the critical variable

135
00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.460
that distinguishes our remembering self

136
00:08:46.460 --> 00:08:54.320
from our experiencing self. Time has very little impact on the story. Now the

137
00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:59.460
remembering self does more than remember and tell stories. It is actually the one

138
00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:03.720
that makes decisions because if you have a patient who has had say two

139
00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:05.620
colonoscopies with two different

140
00:09:05.620 --> 00:09:12.559
surgeons and is deciding which of them to choose, then the one that chooses is the one

141
00:09:12.559 --> 00:09:18.460
that has the memory that is less bad, and that's the surgeon that will be chosen.

142
00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:22.879
The experiencing self has no voice in this choice.

143
00:09:22.879 --> 00:09:25.580
We actually don't choose between experiences. We choose between memories of experiences. não tem voz nessa escolha. Na verdade, não escolhemos entre experiências,

144
00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:28.500
escolhemos entre memórias de experiências.

145
00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:31.120
E mesmo quando pensamos no futuro,

146
00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:34.720
não pensamos normalmente em nosso futuro como experiências,

147
00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:46.000
pensamos nosso futuro como memórias antecipadas. FIS FIS

